                <p>Allergies occur when your body overreacts to harmless substances called allergens, which include things like pollens, dust mites, and molds. The allergic person’s body reacts to allergens by releasing chemicals that affect the skin, respiratory system, digestive tract, and more.1 These chemicals ultimately produce symptoms such as sneezing, runny nose, congestion, rash, and swelling. In some cases, allergies can even lead to life-threatening symptoms, such as anaphylaxis.1</p>

