                <h2>What are Allergies?</h2>
                <p>Allergies are a hypersensitive reaction of the immune system to substances that are typically harmless, known as allergens.
                    Allergic reactions can range from mild symptoms like sneezing and rashes to severe anaphylaxis.</p>
                    <br><br><h3>Causes and Risk Factors:</h3>
                    <p>Genetic predisposition plays a significant role in the development of allergies.
                        Environmental factors such as exposure to allergens like pollen, dust mites, pet dander, or certain foods trigger allergic responses.
                        Early childhood exposure to potential allergens can increase the risk of developing allergies later in life.
                    </p>
                   
                    <h3>Symptoms:</h3>
                    <p>Respiratory symptoms include sneezing, coughing, and a runny or stuffy nose.
                        Skin reactions like hives, eczema, or swelling of the face and extremities.
                        Gastrointestinal issues, such as nausea, vomiting, or diarrhea, especially in food allergies.
                        Anaphylaxis, a severe and potentially life-threatening allergic reaction characterized by swelling, difficulty breathing, and a sudden drop in blood pressure.</p>
                   
                    <h3>Treatment Options:                    </h3>
                    <p>Avoidance of known allergens through environmental control measures and dietary restrictions.
                        Medications, including antihistamines, decongestants, and corticosteroids, to alleviate symptoms and manage allergic reactions.
                        Allergy shots (immunotherapy) to desensitize the immune system to specific allergens.</p>
                  
                    
                    <h3>Long-Term Management:                    </h3>
                    <p>Regular monitoring of potential allergen exposure and proactive measures to minimize contact.
                        Education on early recognition of allergic symptoms and appropriate management strategies.
                        Emergency preparedness for severe allergic reactions, including the use of epinephrine auto-injectors when necessary.
                        Collaboration with allergists and healthcare professionals to develop comprehensive allergy management plans.
                        
                        
                        
